# BUILD.md — __APP_NAME__

Build rules for this app: structure, code quality, and tooling conventions.
**Every `build` request reads this file** (alongside `DESIGN.md`) and must
follow it. Record project-specific build decisions here so later builds comply.

> Seeded as a starter — adjust to match how this project actually works.

## Stack

- Preact + TypeScript + SCSS, built with Vite (`@preact/preset-vite`).
- Linting via oxlint (`npm run lint`).
- Mock-data layer is mandatory (see below) — the app must demo with no backend.

## Project structure

```
config/           Tool configs (vite, tsconfig, oxlint, Dockerfile)
public/           Static assets served as-is
src/
  app/            App shell + top-level composition
  pages/          Page-level / route views — one folder per page: pages/<PageName>/
  components/     Feature & UI components — one folder per: components/<feature-or-component>/
    common/       Primitive / core shared components: components/common/<Component>/
  hooks/          Stateful/reusable hooks (incl. useUIState — persisted UI state)
  lib/            Pure utilities + shared constants (storage, throttle, formatters)
  services/api/   ApiClient interface + injection point (index.ts)
  services/cache/ Client-side data cache (when caching is enabled)
  mock/           MockApiAdapter + data/*.json fixtures
  types/          Shared TypeScript types
styles/           Global SCSS: _variables (CSS custom-property tokens), _themes,
                  _mixins, _responsive, _reset, global
```

## Where generated code goes — pages vs. components

Separate **pages** from **components**, and primitives from features:

- **Page request** ("add a settings page", "build a checkout page") → a folder under
  `src/pages/<PageName>/` (e.g. `src/pages/Settings/`). Pages compose components, wire
  data via hooks/services, and own route-level concerns.
- **Component / feature request** ("build a comments widget", "add a rating control")
  → a folder under `src/components/<feature-or-component>/` (e.g.
  `src/components/comments/`). One folder per component, `.tsx` + co-located `.scss`.
- **Common / primitive component** — a raw, core, "common" building block reused
  across pages and features (Button, Input, Modal, Icon, Card, Tooltip, …) → the
  **`src/components/common/<Component>/`** subfolder (e.g. `src/components/common/Button/`).

Rule of thumb: if it's a screen → `pages/`; if it's a self-contained feature/widget →
`components/<feature>/`; if it's a primitive others compose → `components/common/`.
Never dump everything flat into `src/components/`.

## Component design — SOLID

Every component follows SOLID principles:

- **Single-purpose** — one component does one thing. If it grows two
  responsibilities, split it. Break large sections into smaller components.
- **Open/extensible** — extend behavior via props, `children`, and composition
  rather than editing a component's internals or copying it.
- **Substitutable** — variants of a component honor the same prop contract.
- **Narrow interfaces** — props are minimal and specific; don't pass a god-object
  when two fields will do.
- **Depend on abstractions** — components consume the `ApiClient` interface and
  hooks, never a concrete adapter or global singleton directly.

## Code structure — hoist & centralize

- **Hoist within a file.** Order every file top-to-bottom: imports → constants /
  config → type definitions → helper functions → the component/export. No magic
  values or inline helper definitions buried mid-component.
- **Centralize utilities & config.** Pure helpers + shared constants live in
  `src/lib/`; stateful logic in `src/hooks/`. Never scatter the same helper,
  constant, or value across files — define once, import everywhere. (Top-level
  `config/` is for tooling configs, not app code.)
- **Tokens & fonts only.** Reference CSS custom properties — `var(--color-*)` /
  `var(--space-*)` / `var(--radius-*)` and `var(--font-*)` — never raw values. No
  duplicated logic, tokens, or styles.
- **TypeScript.** Explicit prop types; no `any` in a component's public surface.

## Component behavior — intelligent, non-blocking

- **Never block rendering or interaction.** A component renders its shell
  immediately. Do not `await` data before first paint and never freeze the UI.
- **Lazy-loading states are the default.** Data-driven components progress through
  three states: (1) an initial/empty shell, (2) a loader/skeleton while fetching,
  (3) the loaded data. Always render (1) instantly, then (2), then (3).
- **Use caching when available.** If client-side caching is implemented
  (`src/services/cache/` + a `useCachedResource`-style hook), data components read
  through it: serve cached data immediately, revalidate in the background.
- **Throttle bound input handlers.** Inputs with bound event handlers
  (`onInput`, `onScroll`, `onResize`, `onMouseMove`, search-as-you-type, etc.) are
  **throttled to 100ms by default** via a shared `throttle` utility / hook in
  `src/lib/`. Override the interval only when a specific input needs it.

## Reuse & documentation — keep it DRY

- **`COMPONENT_INDEX.md` is the source of truth.** Document **every** new page,
  component, utility, hook, and SCSS module/mixin/helper there: path · one-line
  purpose · reuse-for hint.
- **Consult it before building.** Every new component or feature must check
  `COMPONENT_INDEX.md` first and **reuse or extend** what exists instead of
  duplicating it. Only create something new when nothing fits.
- **Keep `CLAUDE.md` and `README.md` current.** Reflect major features or changes
  in both as they land — don't leave them stale.
- **README must document the data layer.** The generated `README.md` includes a
  short section on connecting a real data service: implement an `HttpApiAdapter`
  against the `ApiClient` interface and swap it in at `src/services/api/index.ts`
  (one line) — no UI changes required.

## The mock-data layer (mandatory)

- UI depends only on `src/services/api/ApiClient.ts` (an interface).
- `src/services/api/index.ts` is the single injection point, wired to `MockApiAdapter`.
- Swapping to a real backend is a one-line change in `index.ts`.
- Fixtures live in `src/mock/data/*.json` and reflect real entities the UI shows.

## Out of scope

- No backend code. No test generation (handled separately).
